1 HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES - FLOOR VERSION
2 STATE OF OKLAHOMA
3 2nd Session of the 60th Legislature (2026)
4 HOUSE
RESOLUTION 1052 By: Pfeiffer
5
6
7
8 AS INTRODUCED
9 A Resolution proclaiming April 22, 2026, as the 27th
Annual Oklahoma 4-H Day at the Capitol.
10
11
12 WHEREAS, the youth of Oklahoma and the nation represent the
13 future, and their development is paramount to the well-being and
14 prosperity of communities across the country; and
15 WHEREAS, for more than a quarter of a century, this annual
16 celebration of 4-H Day at the Capitol provides an opportunity for
17 club members to share their 4-H stories with state leaders; and
18 WHEREAS, 4-H is the youth development component of the Oklahoma
19 State University and Langston University Extension programs geared
20 toward young people ages 5 to 19; and
21 WHEREAS, for nearly 120 years, 4-H has helped thousands of club
22 members develop life skills such as leadership, decision making,
23 time management, and civic engagement; and
24
HR1052 HFLR Page 1
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.

1 WHEREAS, programming in 4-H is changing continually to meet the
2 needs of today's youth; and
3 WHEREAS, the Oklahoma 4-H Youth Development Program reinforces
4 the learn-by-doing philosophy through hands-on, experiential
5 learning opportunities; and
6 WHEREAS, 4-H reaches more than 180,000 participants each year
7 through membership, project clubs, and school enrichment; and
8 WHEREAS, OSU Extension and Langston University 4-H'ers
9 participate in STEM, civic engagement, healthy living, leisure
10 sciences, natural resources, and agriculture programs; and
11 WHEREAS, dedicated and committed volunteers, mentors, and
12 supporters play a pivotal role in the success of the organization;
13 and
14 WHEREAS, youth who participate in 4-H are four times more likely
15 to make contributions to their communities; and
16 WHEREAS, there are more than 1,300 adult volunteer leaders who
17 serve as mentors and provide leadership while fostering positive
18 adult/youth partnerships; and
19 WHEREAS, youth volunteers develop life skills by serving as
20 mentors/role models and provide leadership to club members; and
21 WHEREAS, 4-H provides programming beyond traditional
22 agricultural projects, including food and nutrition, horticulture,
23 photography, robotics, community development, companion animals and
24 more; and
HR1052 HFLR Page 2
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.

1 WHEREAS, youth participating in 4-H are encouraged to share with
2 state leaders how 4-H is making communities better through project
3 work and service learning activities; and
4 WHEREAS, adult volunteer leaders and club members combined
5 annually contribute more than 100,000 volunteer hours to the
6 betterment of Oklahoma; and
7 WHEREAS, 4-H members continue to work together and follow the
8 motto to "Make the Best Better" in all that they do; and
9 WHEREAS, the annual Oklahoma 4-H Day at the Capitol provides an
10 opportunity to share with state leaders the positive impact they
11 have on their communities, counties, state, and show that they are
12 "Beyond Ready".
13 NOW, THEREFORE, BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES
14 OF THE 2ND SESSION OF THE 60TH OKLAHOMA LEGISLATURE:
15 THAT the Oklahoma House of Representatives recognizes April 22,
16 2026, as the 27th Annual 4-H Day at the Capitol in Oklahoma,
17 celebrating youth who have made an impact on the community and who
18 are stepping up to the challenges of a complex and changing world,
19 and continuing to share the positive impact Oklahoma 4-H has on our
20 youth, our communities, and our state, because "We Are Oklahoma 4-
21 H".
22
23 DIRECT TO CALENDAR.
